<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-08-12T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-08-12T03:00:00-05:00" n="417" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d417">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/9298: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-08-12T16:00:00+08:00">August 12, 1937—4
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received August 12—6:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>455. Mayor Yui reported abandoned civic center headquarters and city
                                government is reported moving to Minghong, about 15 miles west of
                                Shanghai. I have requested Americans in outlying areas to come
                                within the Settlement and usual defence lines, as have British.
                                Chinese panicky with heavy exodus to Settlement south of Soochow
                                Creek.</p>
                            <p>Repeated to Nanking and Peiping.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>